#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
Multi-book fill script for three missing chapters:
  - 2 Kings ch 20 (mkt-context): Hezekiah&#x2019;s illness, Babylonian envoys, Siloam tunnel
  - 1 Chronicles ch 18 (mkt-context): David&#x2019;s campaigns, parallel to 2 Sam 8
  - 2 Samuel ch 10 (mkt-christ): Ammonite war — David&#x2019;s loyal love rejected/type of Christ

Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-fill-2kings20-1chron18-2sam10.py
"""

import json
from pathlib import Path

ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# ── 2 Kings 20 — mkt-context ─────────────────────────────────────────────────

TWO_KINGS_CONTEXT = {
    "20": {
        "1": "<p>The chapter&#x2019;s events are set &#x201C;in those days&#x201D; — a redactional note anchoring the illness to the period of Sennacherib&#x2019;s invasion (2 Kgs 18-19; Isaiah 36-39 presents these events in a different sequence, placing the embassy before the Assyrian crisis). Isaiah son of Amoz is simultaneously the prophet who announced YHWH&#x2019;s deliverance of Jerusalem from Assyria and who now announces Hezekiah&#x2019;s personal death sentence. The same prophetic word that saved the city does not automatically save the king.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Turning the face to the wall (<em>wayyāsoḇ ʾeṯ-pānāyw ʾel-haqqîr</em>) is a gesture of private, intense prayer — withdrawing from public space into intimate address to YHWH. Ancient Near Eastern palaces had the sick king&#x2019;s chamber as the most private interior room; the wall itself becomes the boundary between ordinary reality and the space of prayer. The verb <em>hitpallēl</em> (reflexive of <em>pallēl</em>, to intercede) marks this as formal petitionary prayer, not mere lamenting.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Hezekiah&#x2019;s prayer invokes two key Deuteronomic covenant terms: <em>ʾĕmeṯ</em> (faithfulness, reliability, covenant truth — the quality of walking in integrity with YHWH&#x2019;s instruction) and <em>lēḇāḇ šālēm</em> (whole heart, undivided loyalty — the Shema&#x2019;s ideal of loving YHWH with all one&#x2019;s heart). His appeal is covenant-confidence, not presumption: he has done what YHWH asks, and he appeals to YHWH&#x2019;s own covenant character (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) to hear.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The spatial note — &#x201C;before Isaiah had left the middle court (<em>haḥāṣēr hattîḵônāh</em>)&#x201D; — is remarkable. The divine response comes so immediately that the prophet has barely departed the royal chamber. The palace&#x2019;s three-zone structure (inner chamber, middle court, outer court) reflects ANE palatial architecture; Isaiah is still in the transitional space when YHWH speaks. The immediacy underscores that YHWH heard the prayer as it was prayed.</p>",
        "5": "<p><em>nāḡîḏ-ʿammî</em> — &#x201C;leader of my people&#x221D; — is a deliberately archaic title (used of Saul in 1 Sam 9:16 and of David in 2 Sam 7:8) that emphasizes Hezekiah&#x2019;s role as YHWH&#x2019;s appointed steward rather than an autonomous monarch. The oracle promises healing and access to the temple on the third day — an act of restoration to full covenant participation. &#x201C;The God of your father David&#x221D; grounds the promise in the Davidic covenant.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The addition of fifteen years is a specific, measurable promise — unusual in prophetic oracle, which typically deals in general terms. Fifteen years can be correlated with historical records: Hezekiah began reigning at twenty-five (2 Kgs 18:2) and reigned twenty-nine years total, placing this illness around year fourteen. The deliverance of Jerusalem is paired with the personal healing as a single divine act — YHWH rescues both king and city simultaneously.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The fig poultice (<em>dᵉḇeleṯ tᵉʾēnîm</em>) is a pressed cake of dried figs applied to the skin inflammation (<em>šᵉḥîn</em>). Figs as medicine appear in Ugaritic medical texts and throughout the ancient Near East — the antiseptic and emollient properties of figs were recognized empirically. Isaiah prescribes the remedy as YHWH&#x2019;s instruction, combining prophetic word and medical intervention. The parallel account in Isaiah 38:21 makes clear that the poultice and the oracle belong together.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Hezekiah&#x2019;s request for a confirming sign (<em>ʾôṯ</em>) operates within a well-established OT pattern: Moses (Exod 4:1-9), Gideon (Judg 6:17), and Isaiah&#x2019;s offer to Ahaz (Isa 7:11) all involve signs that confirm prophetic promises. The contrast with Ahaz is significant: Ahaz refused to ask for a sign (Isa 7:12) out of false piety that was actually faithlessness; Hezekiah asks openly, which is covenant confidence.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Isaiah offers a choice between a natural phenomenon (shadow advancing ten steps — the expected direction in the afternoon) and an apparently impossible one (shadow reversing). The Hebrew <em>maʿălôṯ</em> means &#x201C;steps&#x22 or &#x201C;degrees&#x221D; — the same word used in the Psalms of Ascent. The &#x201C;steps of Ahaz&#x221D; (<em>maʿălôṯ ʾĀḥāz</em>) were either a monumental staircase or a sundial-like stepped device; the Isaiah 38:8 parallel confirms the same phenomenon.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Hezekiah chooses the reversal because advancing the shadow is the easy, natural direction. Asking for the reversal demonstrates that the sign is genuinely miraculous — not a coincidence. The logic is sound: the confirming sign must be more extraordinary than mere natural progression. The shadow reversal serves as an analogue to Hezekiah&#x2019;s own reversal — his death sentence reversed by divine intervention.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Isaiah&#x2019;s prayer brings the shadow back ten steps on the steps of Ahaz. The mechanism is left unexplained — as with Elijah and the rain, the narrator is unconcerned with secondary causation. This is one of the more precisely reported miracles in Kings: a specific number of steps, a specific device, a specific direction. Isaiah 38:8 preserves an independent version of the same event in a poetic context.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Merodach-Baladan (Akkadian: Marduk-apla-iddina II) is documented extensively in Assyrian annals — a Chaldean tribal leader who controlled Babylon intermittently between 721 and 703 BCE. He was a persistent opponent of Assyrian hegemony who repeatedly raised coalition resistance against Sargon II and Sennacherib. His embassy to Hezekiah was politically calculated: both kingdoms shared an enemy. The mention of Hezekiah&#x2019;s illness as the embassy&#x2019;s stated occasion is politely diplomatic — the real motive was anti-Assyrian coordination.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Hezekiah&#x2019;s display of his treasury (<em>bayiṯ nᵉḵōṯōh</em>) was both culturally normal and politically unwise. Diplomatic receptions commonly involved displaying royal wealth as a statement of power and reliability as an ally. The catalogue — silver, gold, spices, fine oil, armory, everything in the storehouses — matches the kinds of resources listed in Assyrian tribute records. The prophet&#x2019;s subsequent condemnation is not about the act per se but about the orientation of trust: Hezekiah&#x2019;s look toward Babylon rather than YHWH.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Isaiah&#x2019;s questioning technique — drawing out Hezekiah&#x2019;s own account before delivering the oracle — is a standard prophetic method (cf. Elijah and Hazael in 2 Kgs 8; Nathan and David in 2 Sam 12). The questions make Hezekiah the narrator of his own judgment. The answer &#x201C;from a far land, from Babylon&#x201D; is freighted: Babylon is where the judgment will return.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Hezekiah&#x2019;s complete answer — &#x201C;there was nothing in my treasuries that I did not show them&#x221D; — becomes the template for the oracle. The totality of the display corresponds to the totality of the announced dispossession. The rhetorical structure is precise: what was shown completely will be taken completely.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The formula &#x201C;hear the word of the LORD&#x221D; (<em>šᵉmaʿ dᵉḇar-YHWH</em>) introduces the judgment oracle proper. It signals a shift from interrogative dialogue to authoritative divine speech. In the broader canonical context, Hezekiah&#x2019;s acquiescence to the display of his treasures to Babylon anticipates the theological diagnosis of Judah&#x2019;s eventual fall: alliance with worldly powers rather than trust in YHWH.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The oracle precisely mirrors Hezekiah&#x2019;s disclosure: &#x201C;everything in your house...everything your ancestors stored up...will be carried to Babylon.&#x221D; The <em>hinnēh yāmîm bāʾîm</em> (behold, days are coming) formula introduces a time-delayed judgment — certain in its coming, deferred in its arrival. The 586 BCE Babylonian destruction is the historical fulfillment; the oracle stands as both prophecy and explanation of why the exile happened.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The oracle extends to Hezekiah&#x2019;s descendants: some will be taken to Babylon as eunuchs (<em>sārîsîm</em>) in the palace. <em>Sārîs</em> in this context denotes royal court officers — whether physically castrated or simply palace servants is disputed, but the word carries both meanings in the OT. Jewish tradition identifies the fulfillment in Daniel and his three companions (Dan 1:3-7), who are brought to Babylon and placed in the royal court.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Hezekiah&#x2019;s response — <em>ṭôḇ dᵉḇar-YHWH ʾăšer dibbarṯā</em> (&#x201C;good is the word of the LORD that you have spoken&#x221D;) — is deliberate submission to divine judgment. His follow-up question, &#x201C;will there not be peace and stability in my days?&#x221D; has divided interpreters: is it relief (the calamity is deferred past his lifetime) or a reasonable hope that his reform will delay judgment? The Chronicler omits this verse. The MKT preserves the ambiguity, which may be intentional — Hezekiah&#x2019;s faith is genuine but limited by temporal perspective.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The Siloam tunnel (<em>hattᵉʿālāh</em> — the conduit) is one of the most important archaeological confirmations of a biblical account. Hezekiah&#x2019;s engineers cut a 533-meter tunnel through solid limestone to bring water from the Gihon Spring to the Pool of Siloam inside the city walls — in preparation for the Assyrian siege. The Siloam Inscription (discovered 1880, now in Istanbul) records the moment the two teams tunneling from opposite ends met in the middle. The pool (<em>bᵉrêḵāh</em>) is referenced in Isa 22:11 and by this note in Kings.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Hezekiah&#x2019;s burial formula — sleeping with his ancestors — is standard, but the transition to Manasseh marks one of the sharpest reversals in the book of Kings. The narrative has just celebrated Hezekiah as Judah&#x2019;s most faithful king since David (2 Kgs 18:5); his son will be remembered as the most wicked (2 Kgs 21:9-16). The juxtaposition is a theological statement about individual faithfulness and covenantal continuity: one generation&#x2019;s reform cannot secure the next&#x2019;s.</p>"
    }
}

# ── 1 Chronicles 18 — mkt-context ────────────────────────────────────────────

ONE_CHRONICLES_CONTEXT = {
    "18": {
        "1": "<p>1 Chronicles 18 is a near-verbatim parallel to 2 Samuel 8, the administrative summary of David&#x2019;s military and territorial expansion. The Chronicler&#x2019;s inclusion of this chapter (with minor variants) signals its importance in establishing David as Israel&#x2019;s imperial king whose conquests fund the temple project. The defeat of the Philistines and capture of Gath secured David&#x2019;s western flank — Gath was the closest Philistine city to Judah and a perennial threat.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Moab&#x2019;s subjugation is historically and narratively significant: the Moabites were traditional enemies but also the people of Ruth (David&#x2019;s great-grandmother). 2 Samuel 8:2 records the grim detail of measuring the Moabites by rope — a war atrocity the Chronicler omits. Here the Chronicler simply notes tribute and subjection, presenting David&#x2019;s empire building without its more troubling elements, in keeping with the Chronicler&#x2019;s idealized portrait of David.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Hadadezer king of Zobah (Aram-Zobah) controlled a powerful north-Syrian territory. His campaign &#x201C;to establish his dominion at the Euphrates River&#x221D; — whether extending it or reasserting it — brought him into conflict with David&#x2019;s expanding influence. The location &#x201C;near Hamath&#x221D; (2 Chr 18:3 LXX: &#x201C;by the Euphrates at Hamath&#x221D;) places the battle at the northern extremity of the land promised to Israel (Gen 15:18; Deut 1:7).</p>",
        "4": "<p>The hamstringing of 1,000 chariot horses while keeping 100 reflects Deuteronomic law: the king shall not multiply horses (Deut 17:16). The Chronicler preserves the 7,000 cavalry of 1 Chr 18:4 vs. 2 Sam 8:4&#x2019;s 1,700 — likely a textual transmission difference. The dedication of captured horses to YHWH through hamstringing acknowledges that military power belongs to YHWH rather than to the king&#x2019;s stable.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Aram-Damascus dispatched forces to reinforce Hadadezer — a coalition that David defeated comprehensively. The 22,000 Syrians killed is a number that marks this as a decisive, not merely defensive, victory. The elimination of Damascus as an independent military power opened Syria to Israelite influence for a generation.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Garrison placement in Damascus (<em>wayyāśem ḏāwîḏ baʾărām Dammeśeq niṣṣāḇîm</em>) transforms a military victory into an administrative occupation. The Syrians become tribute-paying subjects. The Chronicler&#x2019;s theological gloss — &#x201C;the LORD gave David victory wherever he went&#x221D; (<em>wayyôšaʿ YHWH ʾeṯ-Dāwîḏ bᵉḵōl ʾăšer hālaḵ</em>) — appears after each major campaign and frames all the victories as YHWH&#x2019;s gift rather than David&#x2019;s military genius.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The gold shields (<em>šilṭê hazzāhāḇ</em>) carried by Hadadezer&#x2019;s officers were ceremonial or decorative — prestige items that demonstrated the Syrian king&#x2019;s wealth. David brings them to Jerusalem, beginning the accumulation of temple materials from conquest. 1 Kings 14:26-27 records that Shishak of Egypt later took these shields from Jerusalem, and Rehoboam replaced them with bronze — the trajectory of decline in one detail.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The bronze (<em>nᵉḥōšeṯ</em>) from Tibhath and Chun is explicitly linked to the temple furnishings: &#x201C;with it Solomon made the bronze sea, the pillars, and the bronze vessels.&#x221D; This is a rare prospective note in Chronicles, connecting David&#x2019;s military success to Solomon&#x2019;s construction achievement. David cannot build the temple but his wars provide the raw materials; the temple project is a multi-generational cooperative enterprise.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Tou (or Toi in 2 Sam 8:9) king of Hamath was a traditional enemy of Hadadezer&#x2019;s Aram-Zobah — the enemy of Israel&#x2019;s enemy. His embassy of congratulation (sending his son Hadoram/Joram) establishes the diplomatic principle that Israel&#x2019;s military victories created new possibilities for alliance with previously hostile powers.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Hadoram&#x2019;s mission is to greet David and congratulate him on his victory over Hadadezer — <em>lišʾōl-lô lᵉšālôm</em> (&#x201C;to inquire of his peace/welfare&#x221D;) is the diplomatic vocabulary of treaty relations. He brings tribute of all kinds: gold, silver, and bronze vessels. The Chronicler notes that Hadadezer had been at war with Tou, providing the political context for the congratulation.</p>",
        "11": "<p>David&#x2019;s dedication of all spoils — <em>gam-ʾōṯām qiddaš hammelek Dāwîḏ laYHWH</em> (&#x201C;King David also consecrated them to YHWH&#x221D;) — is the Chronicler&#x2019;s central emphasis. All wealth flows to YHWH&#x2019;s purposes rather than into royal personal enrichment. The list of nations whose spoils are dedicated (Edom, Moab, Ammonites, Philistines, Amalek) maps the full compass of Israel&#x2019;s neighbors.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Abishai son of Zeruiah (Joab&#x2019;s brother) kills 18,000 Edomites in the Valley of Salt (<em>gêʾ-hammelaḥ</em>) — likely the Dead Sea region south of Judah. 2 Samuel 8:13 attributes this victory to David himself; Psalm 60&#x2019;s superscription attributes it to Joab; 1 Chronicles attributes it to Abishai. The variation reflects different aspects of command responsibility in a single campaign, not contradiction.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Garrisons throughout Edom complete the southern frontier — Edom is the last of the four compass points (west: Philistia; east: Moab/Ammon; north: Aram; south: Edom) to be subdued. The Deuteronomic victory formula — &#x201C;YHWH gave David victory wherever he went&#x221D; — closes the military campaign summary and echoes the formula of vv. 6 and 14.</p>",
        "14": "<p><em>wayyimlōk Dāwîḏ ʿal-kol-Yiśrāʾēl wayyᵉhî ʿōśeh mišpāṭ ûṣᵉḏāqāh lᵉḵol-ʿammô</em> — &#x201C;David reigned over all Israel and administered justice and righteousness (<em>mišpāṭ ûṣᵉḏāqāh</em>) to all his people.&#x221D; This is the defining summary of ideal Davidic kingship — the paired terms <em>mišpāṭ</em> (justice, right ordering) and <em>ṣᵉḏāqāh</em> (righteousness, covenant faithfulness) are the Psalter&#x2019;s royal ideal (Ps 72:1-2) and Isaiah&#x2019;s Messianic criterion (Isa 9:6-7; 11:4-5).</p>",
        "15": "<p>The administrative list demonstrates the mature royal bureaucracy: Joab son of Zeruiah as army commander, Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud as herald (<em>mazḵîr</em> — the one who records and announces royal decisions), Zadok and Abimelech as the dual priesthood. The two-priest arrangement reflects the divided northern (Abiathar) and southern (Zadok) priestly traditions that David integrated.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Shavsha as secretary (<em>sōpēr</em> — scribe) confirms the literate bureaucratic infrastructure of David&#x2019;s administration. The name varies across sources (Seraiah in 2 Sam 8:17, Sheva in 2 Sam 20:25, Shavsha here) — likely a scribal transliteration difference for a non-Israelite royal secretary, possibly Egyptian or Canaanite.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Benaiah son of Jehoiada commanded the Cherethites and Pelethites (<em>haKᵉrēṯî wᵉhaPᵉlēṯî</em>) — the royal bodyguard of Aegean/Philistine origin (Cretans and Peleset), foreign mercenaries whose loyalty to the king personally rather than to Israelite tribal factions made them ideal palace troops. David&#x2019;s sons served as &#x201C;the first at the king&#x2019;s side&#x221D; (<em>hāriʾšōnîm lᵉyaḏ hammelek</em>) — a court title of honor, not priesthood as in 2 Sam 8:18.</p>"
    }
}

# ── 2 Samuel 10 — mkt-christ ─────────────────────────────────────────────────

TWO_SAMUEL_CHRIST = {
    "10": {
        "1": "<p>The death of Nahash king of Ammon opens a chapter about loyal love extended across political boundaries. <span class=\"christ-theme\">Nahash had shown <em>ḥeseḏ</em> (loyal love) to David — the exact covenant term — and David resolves to show the same to his son. The pattern of extending covenant faithfulness to the next generation mirrors YHWH&#x2019;s own <em>ḥeseḏ</em> that reaches to thousands of generations (Exod 20:6). What David models toward Hanun is a shadow of the divine loyal love Christ embodies toward those who inherit the promises of the Father.</span></p>",
        "2": "<p><em>ʾeʿeśeh ḥeseḏ ʿim-Ḥānûn ben-Nāḥāš kaʾăšer ʿāśāh ʾāḇîw ʿimmî ḥāseḏ</em> — &#x201C;I will show <em>ḥeseḏ</em> to Hanun son of Nahash as his father showed <em>ḥeseḏ</em> to me.&#x221D; <span class=\"christ-type\">David sends ambassadors of peace to a potentially hostile nation on the sole basis of prior covenant faithfulness — not political calculation but <em>ḥeseḏ</em>. The type anticipates Christ who, while we were enemies, sent his Son in love (Rom 5:8). The initiative of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> comes from David unprompted; so grace comes from Christ unprovoked by merit.</span></p>",
        "3": "<p><em>hᵃlᵉmᵉkabbēḏ Dāwîḏ ʾeṯ-ʾāḇîḵā bᵉʿênêḵā</em> — &#x201C;Do you really think David is honoring your father in your eyes?&#x221D; <span class=\"christ-theme\">The commanders reinterpret David&#x2019;s peace gesture as espionage — the same dynamic by which Christ&#x2019;s messengers are reinterpreted as threats by those who refuse the gospel (John 7:12; 2 Cor 2:15-16). Grace that is not understood as grace will be treated as aggression. The ambassadors of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> become, in the eyes of suspicion, agents of hostile intelligence.</span></p>",
        "4": "<p><em>wayyiqqaḥ Ḥānûn ʾeṯ-ʿaḇḏê Dāwîḏ wayyᵉgallaḥ ʾeṯ-maḥăṣîṯ zᵉqānām</em> — &#x201C;Hanun seized David&#x2019;s servants, shaved half their beards, cut their garments...and sent them away.&#x221D; <span class=\"christ-allusion\">The deliberate humiliation of royal ambassadors — stripping their dignity through beard-shaving and exposure — anticipates the treatment of Christ&#x2019;s servants who are sent into the world. Jesus&#x2019;s parable of the marriage feast (Matt 22:6) and his warnings that servants will be mistreated as the prophets were (Matt 23:34) echo this pattern. The servants who bear the king&#x2019;s word bear his honor; to humiliate them is to humiliate the sender.</span></p>",
        "5": "<p><em>wayyiggad lᵉDāwîḏ</em> — David is told of the humiliation. <span class=\"christ-theme\">His response is pastoral: he sends messengers to meet the shamed men before they reach Jerusalem, telling them to stay in Jericho until their beards have grown — dignifying their shame rather than forcing a public reappearance. The king&#x2019;s concern for the dishonored mirrors Christ&#x2019;s pastoral care for those who suffer for bearing his name (Matt 5:11-12; Rev 2:10). David does not demand their immediate return; he grants time for the shame to pass.</span></p>",
        "6": "<p>The Ammonites recognize they have &#x201C;made themselves a stench to David&#x221D; (<em>bāʾᵃšû ḇᵉDāwîḏ</em>) — they have crossed a point of no return. Their response is to hire mercenary forces from Aram. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The movement from rejection of grace to military escalation mirrors the pattern in Jesus&#x2019;s parable of the tenants (Matt 21:33-46): when the servants are rejected, more are sent; when the son is rejected, judgment follows. Refusal of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> does not neutralize it — it transforms the situation into one of judgment.</span></p>",
        "7": "<p>David sends Joab and the entire army. <span class=\"christ-shadow\">The king who extended peace now extends power — but it is the power that follows the rejection of peace, not the power of aggression. David&#x2019;s military response to the insult done to his ambassadors shadows YHWH&#x2019;s response to the rejection of his Son: the king sending his armies to destroy those who rejected the wedding invitation (Matt 22:7). The narrative structure of peace-offer, rejection, and military consequence recurs at the eschatological level.</span></p>",
        "8": "<p>The battle positions — Ammonites at the city gate, Syrians in the open field — divide the threat into two fronts. Joab&#x2019;s tactical problem is fighting on two sides simultaneously. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The image of the people of God assailed from multiple directions simultaneously recurs in Paul&#x2019;s military metaphors (Eph 6:10-18; 2 Cor 10:3-5) and in the Psalter (Ps 3:1-2; 118:11). The church&#x2019;s double-front battles — external opposition and internal fracture — require the same tactical wisdom Joab employs: differentiated response with unified purpose.</span></p>",
        "9": "<p>Joab &#x201C;selected some of the best men of Israel and arrayed them against the Syrians.&#x221D; His tactical division of forces — elite troops for the stronger threat, the rest under Abishai for the second front — is sound military judgment. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The principle of matching spiritual resources to spiritual threats, concentrating strength where the enemy is strongest, is a pattern Paul articulates when he speaks of spiritual gifts distributed &#x201C;to each one individually as the Spirit wills&#x221D; (1 Cor 12:11) for the church&#x2019;s warfare.</span></p>",
        "10": "<p>Joab places the remaining forces under Abishai his brother, deploying them against the Ammonites. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The sibling command structure — Joab and Abishai, sons of Zeruiah, coordinating across two fronts — models the mutual dependence the NT envisions for the body of Christ. No one front can be abandoned for the sake of the other; the coordinated advance requires trust between leaders who answer to the same king.</span></p>",
        "11": "<p><em>ʾim-teḥĕzaq mimmennî ʾĂram wᵉhāyîṯāh lî lîšûʿāh</em> — &#x201C;if the Syrians are too strong for me, you come and help me; if the Ammonites are too strong for you, I will come and help you.&#x221D; <span class=\"christ-allusion\">Joab&#x2019;s mutual-aid pact with Abishai anticipates Paul&#x2019;s body metaphor: &#x201C;If one member suffers, all suffer together; if one member is honored, all rejoice together&#x221D; (1 Cor 12:26). The willingness to leave one&#x2019;s own battle to reinforce a brother&#x2019;s is the costly solidarity that defines covenant community.</span></p>",
        "12": "<p><em>ḥăzaq wᵉniṯḥazzaq bᵉʿaḏ-ʿammēnû ûḇᵉʿaḏ ʿārê ʾĕlōhênû wYHWH yaʿăśeh haṭṭôḇ bᵉʿênāyw</em> — &#x201C;Be strong, and let us prove ourselves strong for our people and for the cities of our God, and YHWH will do what is good in his sight.&#x221D; <span class=\"christ-allusion\">Joab&#x2019;s battle speech combines human resolve with divine sovereignty. &#x201C;Be strong and prove strong&#x221D; (<em>ḥăzaq wᵉniṯḥazzaq</em>) uses the imperative-reflexive pair that recurs throughout the OT courage formula (Josh 1:6-9; 1 Kgs 2:2). The final clause — &#x201C;YHWH will do what is good in his sight&#x221D; — echoes in the NT as the soldier&#x2019;s trust in Christ the commander (Eph 6:10: &#x201C;be strong in the Lord&#x221D;).</span></p>",
        "13": "<p>Joab advances and the Syrians flee. The reversal is immediate — the coalition that seemed formidable dissolves at Israel&#x2019;s advance. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The pattern of the LORD routing an apparently superior enemy force without the battle fully joining is characteristic of holy-war narratives (cf. the flight of Midian before Gideon, Judg 7:21-22). The victory belongs to YHWH; Israel&#x2019;s role is to advance in faith. The NT transposes this as &#x201C;resist the devil, and he will flee from you&#x221D; (Jas 4:7).</span></p>",
        "14": "<p>When the Syrians flee, the Ammonites follow — the coalition&#x2019;s coherence depends on its strongest member. Joab returns to Jerusalem rather than pursuing — the restraint signals that the goal was protection, not expansion. <span class=\"christ-theme\">Joab&#x2019;s restraint after victory reflects the warfare ethic of the anointed king&#x2019;s armies: sufficient to secure, not driven by vengeance. The NT&#x2019;s ethic of spiritual warfare similarly distinguishes between resisting evil and pursuing personal retribution (Rom 12:21).</span></p>",
        "15": "<p>The Syrians regroup — defeat does not immediately become surrender. Hadadezer summons reinforcements from beyond the Euphrates. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The regrouping of defeated spiritual forces before their final defeat is a pattern recognized in apocalyptic literature (Rev 12:13-17: the dragon&#x2019;s continued assault after being cast down). The temporary setback of evil powers does not mean their final defeat — only Christ&#x2019;s parousia achieves that closure.</span></p>",
        "16": "<p>Hadadezer brings the Syrians from beyond the Euphrates under the command of Shobak, his commander-in-chief. The escalation — from regional coalition to trans-Euphrates reinforcement — marks this as a definitive confrontation. David himself will cross the Jordan to meet this threat directly, not delegating to Joab.</p>",
        "17": "<p>David crosses the Jordan, musters all Israel, and arrives at Helam. <span class=\"christ-type\">The king who extended peace, whose ambassadors were rejected and humiliated, now personally leads the decisive engagement. David&#x2019;s crossing of the Jordan to confront the assembled Gentile coalition is a type of Christ&#x2019;s parousia — the king who sent messengers in peace returns in power to judge those who refused his ambassadors. The personal engagement of the king distinguishes this battle from the delegated operations of Joab.</span></p>",
        "18": "<p>Israel defeats the Syrians comprehensively: 700 chariot crews killed, 40,000 cavalry killed, Shobak (Shobach) the commander mortally wounded. <span class=\"christ-theme\">The defeat of the Gentile coalition under David&#x2019;s personal leadership anticipates the eschatological victory of the Son of David over the nations assembled against Jerusalem (Rev 19:11-21; Ps 2:8-9). The scale and decisiveness of the victory signal that this is not merely a border skirmish but a defining assertion of Davidic sovereignty.</span></p>",
        "19": "<p><em>wayyirʾû kol-hammᵉlāḵîm ʿaḇḏê Ḥăḏadʿezer kî niggᵉpû lipnê Yiśrāʾēl wayyašlimû ʾeṯ-Yiśrāʾēl wayyaʿaḇḏûm</em> — &#x201C;all the kings who served Hadadezer saw they had been defeated by Israel, made peace with Israel, and became their servants.&#x221D; <span class=\"christ-direct\">This verse has a direct NT trajectory: the Gentile kings who served the enemy of God&#x2019;s anointed make peace and become servants of Israel&#x2019;s king. Paul quotes Psalm 8:6 and alludes to Psalm 110:1 to say that &#x201C;every knee shall bow&#x221D; to Christ (Phil 2:10-11). The geopolitical submission of vassal kings to David prefigures the universal submission to the Son of David that the NT declares accomplished in the exaltation of Christ.</span></p>"
    }
}

